Philosophy of George Box

Journal of the American Statistical Association (1976)

  • "All models are wrong, but some are useful."

  • Parsimony

  • "Since all models are wrong the scientist cannot obtain a "correct" one by excessive elaboration. On the contrary following William of Occam [s]he should seek an economical description of natural phenomena."

  • Worrying Selectively

  • "Since all models are wrong the scientist must be alert to what is importantly wrong. It is inappropriate to be concerned about mice when there are tigers abroad."

Motivation

SIR models and friends

  • Compartmental models: work-horse framework for Covid-19 policy advice.
  • Most policy advice derived from deterministic implementations.
  • Readily coupled with economic models (behavioural pattern in \(R_0\), \(R_t\)).
  • Highly flexible, but often difficult to calibrate/identifiability issues.
  • Focus is on the large population limit.

Branching models

  • Small population limit—stochastic nature highly relevant.
  • Focus on different questions: extinction probabilities, time to Malthusian asymptotic growth, etc.
  • Government of Canada back-to-work policy requires an understanding of small population limits (floor plans, team sizes, interaction rules).
  • Useful in other government concerns (prisons, northern communities,…)

Insipration

  • Hellewell et al. Feasibility of controlling COVID-19 outbreaks by isolation of cases and contacts, The Lancet.

  • Branching process model with serial interval distribution.

  • Number of potential secondary cases produced by each individual is drawn from a negative binomial distribution with a mean equal to the reproduction number.

  • Each potential new infection assigned a time of infection drawn from the serial interval distribution.

  • Truncation of the process with an isolation event.

  • In most of their scenarios contact tracing and case isolation is enough to control a new outbreak of COVID-19 within 3 months.

Opportunities for model improvement

  • Move to full continuous time—negative binomial process joined to a truncation process.
  • A generative model offers generating/characteristic functions.
  • Create parsimonious identifiable model with analytical understanding.
  • Motivate the branching process (e.g., negative binomial counting) from distributional components.
  • Inspired by inventory control problems in operational research.

The model

Crump-Mode-Jagers process

  • CMJ described by a triple of random processes, not necessarily independent, \((\lambda_x, \xi_x(\cdot), \chi_x(\cdot))\) for individual \(x\), all iid copies.

  • \(\lambda_x\) is a random variable that denotes an infected person's communicable period.

  • \(\xi_x(t - \sigma_x)\) is the random number of infected people created by an infected person at every moment of her communicable period over the interval \([\sigma_x,t)\); \(\xi(t - \sigma_x) = 0\) if \(t - \sigma_x<0\). \(\mu(dt) = \mathbb{E}(\xi(dt)).\)

  • \(\chi_x(t - \sigma_x)\) is a random characteristic of the infected person within the interval \([\sigma_x,t)\); \(\chi(t - \sigma_x) = 0\) if \(t - \sigma_x<0\). (E.g., \(\chi(t) = \mathbb{1}\{t\in [0,\lambda)\}\) is the number of infectious existing at moment \(t\)).

Gamma negative binomial branching process

Compound Poisson process with the log-series distribution

  • \(Q(t) = \sum_{i=1}^{N(t)} \, Y_i\); \(N(t)\) the random number of events by \(t\) from the Poisson process (exponential waiting time between infectious events).
  • \(\mathbb{P}(Y_i =k) = \frac{-1}{\ln(1-p)}\frac{p^k}{k}\); \(k \in \{1,2,3,\ldots\}\) (the number of people infected at an infectious event).
  • \(\phi_{Q(t)}(u) =\mathbb{E}[e^{iuQ(t)}]= \left(\frac{1-p}{1-pe^{iu}}\right)^{rt}\); the characteristic function for the negative binomial process.
  • \(Q(t) \sim \mathrm{NB}(rt,p)\); with \(\lambda = -r\ln(1-p)\).
  • The negative binomial results from the underlying stochastic process.

Gamma negative binomial branching process

  • The negative binomial process is a Levy process.
  • Subordinate the Levy process with a Gamma process: \(f_{T(t^\prime)}(x) = \frac{b^{at^\prime}}{\Gamma(at^\prime)} x^{a t^\prime-1}e^{-b x}\).
  • The Gamma process truncates the infection process (communicable period): infection count process \(Z(t^\prime)\) has the characteristic function,
  • \(\mathbb{E}[e^{iuZ(t^\prime)}] = \left(1- \frac{r}{b}\ln\left(\frac{1-p}{1-pe^{iu}}\right)\right)^{-at^\prime}\).
  • Mean communicable period: \(at^\prime/b\)
  • Branching model fully described.
  • \(\mathbb{E}\left(\xi(dt)\right) = \frac{rp}{1-p} \left(1- \int_0^t\frac{b^{at^\prime}}{\Gamma(at^\prime)} x^{a t^\prime-1}e^{-b x}\, dx\right)\,dt\)
  • Model parameters: \(\lambda\) (Poisson arrival rate), \(\mu\) (mean of log-series), \(a\), and \(b\) (Gamma parameters).

Analytical control

  • Extinction probabilities.

  • Expectations over random characteristics (e.g., total infected, current infected population) and Malthusian parameters from renewal theory:

  • \(m(t) = \mathbb{E}\left(\chi(t)\right) + \int_0^t m(t-u) \,\mathbb{E}\left(\xi(du)\right)\).

  • Mean total number infected given extinction from random graphs with arbitrary vertex degree distributions (Newman, Strogatz, and Watts cond-mat/0007235)

.

Simulation

The infected compartment

Probability of extinction

Branching process extinction probability

  • \(G(t;s) = \mathbb{E}\left[s^{Z(t)}\left|\right.Z(0)=1\right]\)
  • \(\xi(t) = \#\{\delta_i: \delta_i \leq t\} = \sum_{i=1}^\infty \mathbb{1} \{\delta_i \leq t\}.\)
  • \(q= \mathbb{P}\left(\lim_{t\to\infty} Z(t) =0\right) = \lim_{t\to\infty} G(t;0)\)
  • \(q = \lim_{t\to\infty} \mathbb{E}\left[ \prod_{i=1}^{\xi(t)}G(t - \delta_i;0)\right]= \mathbb{E}\left[q^N \right]\)
  • For our process: \[q = \left(1- \frac{r}{b}\ln\left(\frac{1-p}{1-pq}\right)\right)^{-at^\prime}\]

Extinction probabilities

Graph analysis

  • Graph component size: out-going vertex distribution is our branching process.
  • Compute average size given extinction: graph size distribution excluding the giant component (if exists).
  • Consistent with the renewal equation before phase transition.

Graph analysis: component size

  • Average size of graph, \(\bar s\), given extinction (Newman, Strogatz, and Watts cond-mat/0007235).
  • Extinction a.s. (renewal theory matches) \[\bar s = \frac{1}{1 - G^\prime(1)}\]
  • Malthusian parameter > 0; extinction probability \(q\) \[\bar s = 1 + \frac{zq}{1 - G^\prime(q)}\]
  • \(z = \frac{1 - q}{\int_u^1 G(s)\,ds}\)

Simulation analysis

Simulation analysis

  • Build sample paths to examine best/wort cases.
  • Graphically observe the onset of the compartmental model limit.
  • See the distribution of extinct populations.
  • Sensitivity analysis around model parameters and the communicable period.

Simulation with intervention

  • Contact tracing and isolation: switch from communicable period distribution \(x_0\) to a new commumicable period distribution \(x_1\) with probability \(p\).
  • \(U_x(t) = \prod_{j =0}^1[Z_j(t)]^{\mathbb{1}\{y = j\}}\); \(y\sim\text{Bin}(1,p)\)
  • \(\mathbb{E}(U_x(t)) = (1-p)\,\mathbb{E}(Z_0(t)) + p\,\mathbb{E}(Z_1(t))\): sensitivity/iso-contour analysis.
  • Simulate the effect of the intervention—changes to extinction probabilities.
  • Working with PSPC Real Property division for back-to-work policy guidance.

Simulation with intervention

Estimation

A complete history of an outbreak

  • We define a complete history of an outbreak as a set of \(N\) observations taking the form of a 6-tuple:

  • \((i,j,b_{i},d_{i},m_{i},o_{i})\)

  • \[\begin{align} i &\phantom{=} \text{index of individual}\\ j &\phantom{=} \text{index of parent}\\ b_{i} &\phantom{=} \text{time of birth}\\ d_{i} &\phantom{=} \text{time of death}\\ m_{i} &\phantom{=} \text{number of offspring birth events}\\ o_{i} &\phantom{=} \text{number of offspring} \end{align}\]

Parameter inference from a complete history

  • With the following summary statistics:
  • \[\begin{align} L & = \sum_{i} d_{i} - b_{i} & \lambda & = \prod_{i} (d_{i} - b_{i})\\ M & = \sum_{i} m_{i} & O & = \sum_{i} o_{i} \nonumber \end{align}\]
  • resample the GNBBP parameters as follows:
  • \[\begin{align} p\,|\,r,L,O &\sim \text{Beta}\left(a_{0} + O,b_{0} + r L\right)\\ r\,|\,p,L,M &\sim \text{Gamma}\left(\eta_{0}+M,\rho_{0}-L\ln(1-p)\right)\\ \beta\,|\,\alpha,L,N &\sim \text{Gamma}\left(\gamma_{0}+\alpha N,\delta_{0}+L\right)\\ \alpha\,|\,\beta,\Lambda,N &\sim \text{GammaShape}\left(\epsilon_{0}\Lambda,\zeta_{0}+N,\theta_{0}+N\right) \end{align}\]

Dealing with noisy observations

  • While an outbreak is in progress, we will not have complete observations:
  • The variables \(d_{i}\), \(m_{i}\), \(o_{i}\) will be right-censored for many individuals.
  • We may not fully know the mapping of offspring to parents.
  • Our observations of birth times \(b_{i}\) may be noisy.
  • We might not observe some individuals at all, etc, etc.
  • In these cases, we use a forward filtering backwards sampling approach.
  • With \((\alpha,\beta,r,p)\) and our observed data fixed, generate a synthetic complete history consistent with observed data.
  • Using synthetic complete history, resample \((\alpha,\beta,r,p)\).

Example: Augmentation of censored observations

  • While an outbreak is in progress, many individuals will be censored at the end of our observation window \(C\). We augment these to complete records as follows:
  • Generate synthetic time of death \(d_{i}'\) by sampling off of the tail of the gamma distribution; i.e., drawing from the gamma conditioned on surviving at least \(C-b_{i}\)
  • \[\begin{align} z & \sim \text{GammaTail}(\alpha,\beta,C-b_{i}) \nonumber \\ d_{i}' & = b_{i} + z \nonumber \end{align}\]

Example: Augmentation of censored observations

  • Draw additional arrivals:
  • \[m' \sim \text{Poisson}(-r (d_{i}-T)\log(1-p))\]
  • Draw additional offspring at each arrival \(k=1,\ldots,m'\)
  • \[o_{k}' \sim \text{Logarithmic}(p)\]

Example: Working from birth times only

  • Assume we only observe the set of birth times \(\left\{b_{i}\right\}\).
  • For a given individual \(i\) (or birth time, if multiple coincidental arrivals), randomly assign a parent \(j<i\) using weights.
  • \[w_{j} = \frac{\Gamma(\alpha,\beta (b_{i}-b_{j}))}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\]
  • Assign death times to individuals, conditioned on last birth of assigned offspring as appropriate.
  • Complete the history by generating additional offspring for those individuals with \(d_{i}\) after the censoring time as per previous slide.

Summary

Summary

  • An extension of Hellewell et al. that results in a complete generative process.
  • Generating/characteristic function gives us analytic control.
  • Distributions permit estimation through Markov Chain Monte Carlo methods, particle filters, etc.
  • Can examine contact tracing and other propagation interruption scenarios.
  • Help set policy in small populations (back-to-work, headquarter floor plans, prisons, borders, etc.)
